====2.4.1 DAOs.====

<blockquote>
  Technology for democracy must be understood by the vast majority of citizens. It is the technology that we do not control the one that it is used to control us.
</blockquote>
[https://twitter.com/earlkman '''Emiliano Kargieman'''], space hacker (1975).

Building decentralized organizations has been attempted in the past. ''Distributed Autonomous Organizations'' (or DAOs) aim to be blockchain entities constructed with smart contracts that entirely automate decision processes and can run without any kind of human oversight. The code itself is meant to be the ultimate arbiter, hence these organizations claim that ''code is law''. But experience has taught that ''bugs are law'' too: when German company [http://slock.it Slock.it] implemented [http://www.coindesk.com/understanding-dao-hack-journalists/ the largest crowdfunded DAO in May 2016 able to raise over USD 100 million], a hacker exploited the code using a security hole in the smart contract controlling all funds triggering a recursive call that leaked USD 55 million worth of ether from this DAO.

We believe there is a clear lesson to be learned from this: the need for governance cannot be abstracted. Voting matters. The neural networks with the accumulated trained sets of a lifetime each human carries in one's head is a fundamental resource for savvy decision making. DAO driven entities surrender the political frontier between mankind and machines entirely to the machines. It is a well known risky path: financial markets have been dealing with [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flash_crash flash crashes] and erratic glitches from trading bots [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Monday_(1987) since the introduction of the first computers]. Bitcoin's ongoing scaling debate between those who build its software and those who provide mining hardware suffers from the lack of a clear protocol for decision making often stagnating innovation. The vote is an instrument that helps streamline decision processes, taking the legitimate input of all interested parties into account. Nonetheless, we are not against a complimentary implementation of AIs interacting with the system. Sovereign implementations can include AIs as participants that can even receive ''VOTE'' delegations and represent members. But it is the act of voting, rather than code that can escape the comprehension of participants, what keeps the system as a whole auditable, transparent and democratic.

===2.5 Smart Contracts.===

The modern architecture for computing machines designed by John von Neumann specified that computers should be built with a rapid access memory (RAM), an information storage device and a central processing unit (CPU). The arrangement of these components led to the [https://www.amazon.it/Turings-Cathedral-Origins-Digital-Universe/dp/1400075998 ''big bang'' of the digital universe] that took the world by surprise in the second half of the 20th century. With this in mind we focused on building an efficient design for a governance machine able to operate with blockchains that keeps its human operators as sovereign rulers by means of the vote. In the same way bits move in computers signalling a <code>true</code> or <code>false</code> state, ''VOTEs'' signal a boolean state for institutional decisions recorded under smart contracts.

''VOTE'' tokens operate within the institutional boundaries created by this set of contracts: <code>Organizations</code>, <code>Members</code>, <code>Decisions</code>, <code>Ballots</code> and <code>Budgets</code>. These are the building blocks that help create a governance circuit that can scale to operate liquid democracies within communities of any size.

[[File:/images/vote-liquid-democracy-smart-contracts.png|VOTE Liquid Democracy smart contracts..]]

====2.5.1 <code>Organizations</code>====

The entity or institution implementing a Sovereign instance is referred as an ''Organization''. Every Organization has a ''constitutional smart contract'' able to determine how VOTEs will be allocated to its members. Allocation conditions are a prerogative of the organization depending on its goals: in some cases it can be aligned with financial rights (e.g. the shareholders of a corporation getting one ''VOTE'' per share); in other cases can be assigned based on an egalitarian distribution to all members (e.g. tax payers within a jurisdiction each getting a same amount of ''VOTEs'').

====2.5.2 <code>Members</code>====

Every Organization has members that get the right to vote on the decisions of the organization. Membership approval is defined in the ''constitutional smart contract'' of the organization, setting how open or closed as an institution this entity will be. Some organizations may allow for members to be instantly approved once they register with their credentials or pay a membership fee, while others might require an approval of pre-existing members that can vote on the status of an applicant as member.

A strict definition in the membership criteria of an organization is key for the trust on any democratic environment. Among the most common ways to subvert an election is the manipulation of voter registry. Securing this aspect with cryptographic means as well as an approval protocol is critical. Once a member is approved within an organization, he or she gets a specific amount of ''VOTEs'' to be used for its governance.

Compatibility with decentralized identity protocols is encouraged for the purpose of guaranteeing decentralized governance. The [https://opencreds.github.io/did-spec/ specification of DIDs (decentralized identifiers analogous to the web's URIs)], proposed by the [https://www.w3.org/ W3C] enabling self-sovereign verifiable digital identity is recommended.

====2.5.3 <code>Decisions</code>====

An organization consists of a collection of contracts each describing a decision to be made by the members. In the ''constitutional smart contract'' of an organization it can be defined whether any member or a subset with special rights (e.g. members that have a minimum amount of ''VOTEs'') can post an open decision to be voted. A decision in its most basic form has these properties:

* <code>Description</code>: Text of the decision to be made.
* <code>Tags</code>: Categories that describe this decision within the organization. This helps members navigate across decisions, define areas or teams within an organization and limit the scope of a delegation of ''VOTEs'' under liquid democracies. If the implementation is done with blockchain environments managing a fixed taxonomy, a common distributed language for tags helps making the democratic environment of an organization more fair as it avoids members trying to control naming conventions for their own benefit.
* <code>Signatures</code>: Members that are authoring the proposal. It can remain anonymous if an organization's governance rules allows it.
* <code>Ballot</code>: The presented options for voters to participate on this decision.
* <code>Budget</code>: An optional element that may include locked funds in a cryptocurrency address that can trigger an action if a decision is voted in support.
* <code>Timespan</code>: For the final tally, an open poll must also set its scope in time and define the kind of decision being made. There are two types of decisions:
** '''Tactical''' (''Time limited''): These are contracts that receive ''VOTEs'' until a closing date is met, where a given block height within the blockchain implementing the ''VOTE'' smart contracts can be set as the end line for the electoral process. Once all transactions have been tallied and a final result is recorded, all tokens get returned to the corresponding voters and can be used again on future decisions.
** '''Strategical''' (''Time unlimited''): Never-ending open polls that are perpetually registering the consensus of a decision state. ''VOTEs'' can be retrieved by voters at any given time if they feel the need to discontinue their voice in support or rejection of a decision. But as long as the token is assigned to signal a preference on a contract ballot without closing date, it is part of the strategical decision. A common use for strategical decisions can be the members signalling approval of other members within the community of an organization.

====2.5.4 <code>Ballot</code>====

A decision can be implemented with any possible ballot design according to the specifications defined in the ''constitutional smart contract'' of the organization. The building blocks for a ballot are its <code>Interface</code>, <code>Options</code> and <code>Criteria</code>.

=====2.5.4.1 <code>Interface</code>=====

By default Sovereign provides the most commonly used choice mechanisms for ballot interaction. Further innovation on ballot interfaces is encouraged.

* '''Single Choice''': One selectable option.
* '''Multiple Choice''': One or more selectable options.
* '''[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranked_voting Ranked Choice]''': Sortable options as ranked preferences.

=====2.5.4.2 <code>Options</code>=====

In order to enable the information processing of ''VOTEs'', ballots carry boolean values expressed in their options. This lets ''VOTE'' transactions signal a ''decision state'' that will act as a force modeling the institutional choices for the implementing organization. This makes all decentralized organizations also into programmable institutions. Options can then be:

* <code>True</code>: It will signal a <code>true</code> boolean value if selected (often described with 'Yes' or 'Positive' label strings).
* <code>False</code>: Signals a <code>false</code> state (e.g. can display 'No' or 'Negative' labels).
* <code>Linked</code>: The option is connected to another decision within the organization.
* <code>Candidate</code>: A member or list of members from the organization. This helps elect authorities within the organization or it can be used for membership approvals.

=====2.5.4.3 <code>Criteria</code>=====

Finally, counting methods for the final or ongoing result of a decision within an organization.

* '''Plurality Voting''': Simple majority wins decision.
* '''Majority Voting''': A minimum percentage is required for winning decision.
* '''[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%27Hondt_method D’Hont method]''': Widely used by Nation-State elections based on member lists.
* '''[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schulze_method Schülze method]''': Commonly used by open source communities and Pirate Parties using ranked choice ballots.

====2.5.5 <code>Budget</code>====

If the final tally of a decision reaches a certain value (<code>true</code> or <code>false</code>), it can then enforce the final decision by unlocking coins to the private key owners of an address or triggering a transaction sending assets to a specific address. Budgets specify the conditions and funds attached to a decision.

