Identity is foundational to the achievement of personal sovereignty, so it must be a foundational building block of any system of voting and organizational governance. From Democracy Earth Foundation's perspective, a vote will always take place within an organization. It can be a Nation-State or a decentralized collective, but it will always be defined by its valid and verifiable membership. Therefore DEF's liquid democracy voting / decision-making platform will be organization-centric, meaning it will codify any organizational membership rules and ratifications related to digitally established identification.

Today’s standard identity systems are based on physical documents and processes, which has inherent limitations. Analogue identity systems put users at risk due to overexposure of information, plus the high risk of information loss or theft. Paper is easily forged, certainly relative to modern cryptography. In addition, nation-state issued IDs are becoming obsolete and are already insecure as populations are traveling and migrating more.

Meanwhile, in our online lives our personal identities are stored in a series of siloed gardens, each belonging to a different app/website/service provider - a situation that has resulted in a usability and privacy disaster for individuals, while creating a multitude of data honeypots for hackers—the breach of which compromises trust in all Internet services.

For that reason, the biggest blockchain opportunity of all is to own, manage and monetize our virtual identity --  an opportunity that today rests solely in the hands of digital conglomerates like Google, Facebook and Twitter.

The evolution of internet identity is the result of trying to satisfy three basic requirements: security (i.e. protected from unintentional disclosure), control (the identity owner enables access to his data) and portability, as in, the user can access their identity without being tied to a particular provider(s).

Recent developments in distributed computing are allowing the rise of  truly self-sovereign identity systems. Asymmetric cryptography ensures security from the user perspective, and trust between peers can arise in a decentralised manner, with the collection of credentials and reputation management. Because anyone can use these identities and the resulting benefits without an intervening authority, they’re called “self-sovereign.”

With trust itself being enabled by technologies and not institutions, the next evolution of the Internet will be the creation of a common identity layer that allows people, organisations and things to have their own self-sovereign identity that is secure, under their control, and always available to them, with no need for intermediary permissions.

